&lt;s&gt;As said [here](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/pull/10676):

&gt; The intuitive way to think of these rules is that immutable locations always have the most specific type inferred for them, whereas mutable locations have a widened type inferred. 

Therefore, in 

    let a: string | number = &#39;foo&#39;;
    a.length; // ok

the type of `a` is inferred as `string`, because `foo` is immutable, but in

    let c: { p: string | number } = { p: &#39;foo&#39; };
    c.p.length; // NOT ok

the type of `c.p` is not narrowed, because `{p: foo}` is mutable.

&lt;/s&gt;

