You can&#39;t do this. But you can wait till the process finish, you can use `FileInfo.IsFileLocked()` to verify if your file is in use.

Sample code:

    public static void Test(){
        FileInfo inf = new FileInfo(&quot;your_file&quot;);
    
        while (inf.IsFileLocked()) {
          Console.WriteLine(&quot;File locked, wait...&quot;);
        };
    }

Important: *Remember to close streams every time you open them, as this may cause file locks.*

Am a bit confused on what the issue is but, from the looks of things, you never close the `FileStream`. When you open a file stream in that manner, the file&#39;s `ShareMode` is set to None so no other process can read/write/delete the file. All you need to really do is change the last line from:

```
entity.file.CopyTo(new FileStream(fullPath, FileMode.Create));
```

to

```
//Opens the file
using (FileStream stream = new FileStream(fullPath, FileMode.Create))
{
    //Copies data from entity.file to stream
    entity.file.CopyTo(stream);
}
//File was released (disposed of) thanks to the using statement
```

After the copy is done, the file is released so other processes will be able to access it.

